  "source": "https://app.excalidraw.com",
  "elements": [
    {
      "id": "ss2Y4cKfcHY78ELXFTVqj",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 621,
      "y": 238,
      "width": 418.4200134277344,
      "height": 225,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "a0",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1572451262,
      "version": 154,
      "versionNonce": 620617726,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771191934028,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Traversal\nI am at NODE A\nI want to get to NODE B\nIn the shortest route\nHow do I do that?\n\nReturn a list of nodes to get from A to B\n\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Traversal\nI am at NODE A\nI want to get to NODE B\nIn the shortest route\nHow do I do that?\n\nReturn a list of nodes to get from A to B\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "m1p8-Xtw5NpTTS-L185t9",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 694,
      "y": 449,
      "width": 8,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "a1",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1546145278,
      "version": 3,
      "versionNonce": 1105119330,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771190523867,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "pJgh1Z-VsHKesOBOZPnGP",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 617,
      "y": 471,
      "width": 591.9400634765625,
      "height": 2000,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "a2",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1596823522,
      "version": 1785,
      "versionNonce": 595760418,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771192580673,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Undirected\n\nBrute Force (Breadth First Search)\nUse queues\n1) Start from A\n2) Go to the next set of nodes and set \n3) Skip all previously met nodes\n4) Go to next neighbor in list made\n5) Keep going till you find B\n\nFIFO\n\nWe should always find B\nGuaranteed find the short path to B\nSpace - O(W)\nWorks well on dense\nTime - O(V+E)\nVertex or Vector or Vertices\n\nDepth First\nKinda pre traversal - FILO\nThis uses a stack\n1) Start with A\n2) Go to the next set of nodes and set \n3) Skip all previously met nodes\n4) Go to next neighbor in stack made\n5) Keep going till you find B\n\nCan find a path faster than breadth first\nSpace - O(D)\nGreat on Sparse Graphs\nTime - O(V+E)\n\nTwo End\n1) Breadth search  from both nodes at once\n2) More efficient than the Breadth First\n\nReduces the number of nodes in the neighbors list\nsince the neighbors lists exponentially grows\nas we traverse farther down\n\nWeighted \nDijkstras\nPriority Queue\n1) Start with A\n2) Go to the next set of nodes and set neighbors\n3) Skip all previously met nodes\n4) Go to next neighbor with the lowest weighted edge\n5) Keep going till you find B\n\nGenerally true to find the shortest path\n  for weighted graphs\nMix of breadth and depth\n\nTo truly solve shortest path is an NP hard\n  problem. NP = Non-polynomial\n\n\nTSP - traveling salesman problem\n\nSalemes\nHas to go to X cities, visiting 1 at a time, no repeats,\ndo it in the shortest route possible\n\nGiven a complete graph with N nodes, how many combinations\nof traversals are there?\n\nfor 4 nodes = 3 * 2 * 1 = 6\n\n6 nodes = 5 * 4 * 3 * 2 * 1 = 120\n\n10 nodes = … = ~360k\n\n15 nodes = … = ~1.3T\n\nAbout 15 seconds and goes exponentially from there. \n\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Undirected\n\nBrute Force (Breadth First Search)\nUse queues\n1) Start from A\n2) Go to the next set of nodes and set \n3) Skip all previously met nodes\n4) Go to next neighbor in list made\n5) Keep going till you find B\n\nFIFO\n\nWe should always find B\nGuaranteed find the short path to B\nSpace - O(W)\nWorks well on dense\nTime - O(V+E)\nVertex or Vector or Vertices\n\nDepth First\nKinda pre traversal - FILO\nThis uses a stack\n1) Start with A\n2) Go to the next set of nodes and set \n3) Skip all previously met nodes\n4) Go to next neighbor in stack made\n5) Keep going till you find B\n\nCan find a path faster than breadth first\nSpace - O(D)\nGreat on Sparse Graphs\nTime - O(V+E)\n\nTwo End\n1) Breadth search  from both nodes at once\n2) More efficient than the Breadth First\n\nReduces the number of nodes in the neighbors list\nsince the neighbors lists exponentially grows\nas we traverse farther down\n\nWeighted \nDijkstras\nPriority Queue\n1) Start with A\n2) Go to the next set of nodes and set neighbors\n3) Skip all previously met nodes\n4) Go to next neighbor with the lowest weighted edge\n5) Keep going till you find B\n\nGenerally true to find the shortest path\n  for weighted graphs\nMix of breadth and depth\n\nTo truly solve shortest path is an NP hard\n  problem. NP = Non-polynomial\n\n\nTSP - traveling salesman problem\n\nSalemes\nHas to go to X cities, visiting 1 at a time, no repeats,\ndo it in the shortest route possible\n\nGiven a complete graph with N nodes, how many combinations\nof traversals are there?\n\nfor 4 nodes = 3 * 2 * 1 = 6\n\n6 nodes = 5 * 4 * 3 * 2 * 1 = 120\n\n10 nodes = … = ~360k\n\n15 nodes = … = ~1.3T\n\nAbout 15 seconds and goes exponentially from there. \n\n\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
